{% set basicMapCode %}<img src="floor-plan.jpg" alt="Office floor plan" usemap="#office" width="800" height="500" />

<map name="office">
  <area shape="rect" coords="40,40,320,220"
    href="/rooms/conference" alt="Conference Hall" />
  <area shape="circle" coords="500,160,80"
    href="/rooms/server" alt="Server Room" />
  <area shape="poly" coords="480,280,760,280,760,460,560,460,480,380"
    href="/rooms/office" alt="Open Office" />
</map>{% endset %}

{% set usemapCode %}<!-- The img references the map by name -->
<img src="diagram.png" alt="Network diagram"
  usemap="#network" width="600" height="400" />

<!-- The map is identified by its name attribute -->
<map name="network">
  <area shape="rect" coords="10,10,200,150"
    href="#router" alt="Main router" />
  <area shape="rect" coords="250,10,450,150"
    href="#switch" alt="Core switch" />
</map>{% endset %}

{% set responsiveIssueCode %}<!-- Native map: pixel coords break at any size other than 800x500 -->
<img src="plan.jpg" alt="Floor plan" usemap="#plan"
  width="800" height="500"
  style="max-inline-size: 100%; block-size: auto;" />

<map name="plan">
  <!-- These coords target exact pixels in the 800x500 image.
       When the image scales to 400px wide, coords still reference
       the original 800px space — hotspots shift off-target. -->
  <area shape="rect" coords="40,40,320,220"
    href="#room-a" alt="Room A" />
</map>{% endset %}

{% set imageMapCode %}<!-- Modern replacement: percentage-based coordinates -->
<image-map>
  <img src="plan.jpg" alt="Floor plan" />
  <map-area shape="rect" coords="5 8 40 44"
    label="Room A" href="#room-a">
    <strong>Room A</strong>
    <p>Rich HTML tooltip content.</p>
  </map-area>
</image-map>{% endset %}

<section>
  <h2>Description</h2>
  <p>The <code>&lt;map&gt;</code> element defines a client-side image map &mdash; a set of clickable regions overlaid on an image. Each region is defined by an <a href="/docs/elements/native/area/"><code>&lt;area&gt;</code></a> child element with pixel-based coordinates. The map is linked to an <a href="/docs/elements/native/img/"><code>&lt;img&gt;</code></a> via the <code>usemap</code> attribute.</p>

  <p>Image maps were designed for fixed-size images in the early web. The coordinate system uses <strong>absolute pixel values</strong>, which means hotspot regions break when the image scales to a different size &mdash; a serious limitation in responsive layouts.</p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Basic Example</h2>

  <p>Hover over a room to see its <code>title</code> tooltip. Click to see the area name in the status bar. This demo renders the image at its native 800&times;500 pixels so the pixel-based coordinates align correctly.</p>

  <iframe
    src="/docs/snippets/demos/map-area-native.html"
    width="800" height="540"
    style="border: 1px solid var(--color-border, #ddd); border-radius: var(--radius-m, 8px); max-inline-size: 100%;"
    loading="lazy"
    title="Native image map demo">
  </iframe>

  <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Image map with three area shapes">{{ basicMapCode | escape }}</code-block>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>How It Works</h2>
  <p>The <code>&lt;map&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;img&gt;</code> are connected through two attributes:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>The <code>&lt;map&gt;</code> element has a <code>name</code> attribute (e.g. <code>name=&quot;office&quot;</code>)</li>
    <li>The <code>&lt;img&gt;</code> has a <code>usemap</code> attribute with a hash reference (e.g. <code>usemap=&quot;#office&quot;</code>)</li>
  </ol>
  <p>The browser renders the image normally. When the user clicks or taps within a region defined by an <code>&lt;area&gt;</code>, the browser navigates to that area&rsquo;s <code>href</code>.</p>

  <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Linking img to map via usemap">{{ usemapCode | escape }}</code-block>
</section>

