  <p>The <code>&lt;map&gt;</code> element also supports <a href="/docs/attributes/">global attributes</a>.</p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>The Responsive Problem</h2>
  <p>Native <code>&lt;map&gt;</code> coordinates are defined in <strong>absolute pixels</strong> matching the image&rsquo;s natural dimensions. Modern layouts scale images fluidly with <code>max-inline-size: 100%</code>, but the coordinate system does not scale with them. The result: hotspot regions drift away from their visual targets as the image shrinks or grows.</p>

  <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Pixel coordinates break at different sizes">{{ responsiveIssueCode | escape }}</code-block>

  <p>Workarounds exist (JavaScript that recalculates coordinates on resize), but they add complexity and fragility. The native element was not designed for responsive use.</p>

  <aside class="note">
    <strong>Recommendation:</strong> For responsive image maps, use the <a href="/docs/elements/web-components/image-map/"><code>&lt;image-map&gt;</code></a> web component. It uses percentage-based coordinates (0&ndash;100) that scale with the image, supports rich HTML tooltips, and provides keyboard navigation.
  </aside>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Modern Alternative</h2>
  <p>Vanilla Breeze provides <a href="/docs/elements/web-components/image-map/"><code>&lt;image-map&gt;</code></a> as a modern replacement for native <code>&lt;map&gt;</code>/<code>&lt;area&gt;</code>:</p>

  <table class="props-table">
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Native <code>&lt;map&gt;</code></th><th>VB <code>&lt;image-map&gt;</code></th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Coordinate system</td><td>Absolute pixels</td><td>Percentages (0&ndash;100)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Responsive</td><td>No</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tooltips</td><td><code>title</code> text only</td><td>Rich HTML content</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Keyboard navigation</td><td>Tab only</td><td>Tab + Arrow keys + Escape</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Visual feedback</td><td>None</td><td>SVG overlay with hover highlight</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Progressive enhancement</td><td>N/A (native)</td><td>Falls back to labeled list</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Modern replacement with percentage coordinates">{{ imageMapCode | escape }}</code-block>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Accessibility</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Every <code>&lt;area&gt;</code> must have an <code>alt</code> attribute describing the linked region</li>
    <li>The <code>&lt;img&gt;</code> itself needs an <code>alt</code> describing the overall image</li>
    <li>Native image maps support keyboard navigation via <kbd>Tab</kbd> between areas</li>
    <li>Screen readers announce area <code>alt</code> text as link text</li>
    <li>No visual focus indicator exists on native areas &mdash; users cannot see which region has focus</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Browser Support</h2>
  <p>The <code>&lt;map&gt;</code> element has universal browser support dating back to the earliest HTML specifications. However, it was designed for an era of fixed-width layouts and offers no adaptation for modern responsive design.</p>
</section>

